    <description>The Sample Return Capsule (SRC) was a system for non-destructively collecting cometary and interstellar dust particles, then storing the samples and returning them to the Earth for detailed analysis. The Sample Return Capsule was about a meter in diameter, and opened like a clamshell, allowing the collecting grid to be deployed into the dust stream to collect samples. It consisted of four main components: the sample collector; the aeroshell (backshell and heat shield); the parachute system; and the avionics. The sample collector was a passive system for collecting dust grains and consisted of an aluminum grid encasing multiple microporous silica aerogel blocks that acted as the dust collectors. The samples were successfully returned to Earth in January 2006.</description>
